                    <persName xml:id="name1405-7" xml:lang="fr-x-fiey" source="#bib1405-2">PAUL D'ÉDESSE</persName>
                    <idno type="URI">http://syriaca.org/person/1405</idno>
                    <idno type="FIEY">255</idno>
                    <idno type="FIEY">339</idno>
                    <sex value="M" source="#bib1405-2">male</sex>
                    <floruit source="#bib1405-2" from="0418" syriaca-computed-start="0418" to="0435" syriaca-computed-end="0435">0418-0435</floruit>
                    <note type="abstract" xml:id="abstract-en-1405">
                        <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/1405">Paul of Edessa</persName> was a bishop from the Italian peninsula who left his see and travelled to <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/78">Edessa</placeName> where, in disguise, he was hired into service as a household servant by <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/1321">John of Edessa</persName>, a priest. The two
          lived a life of prayer and spiritual companionship. They travelled to <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/563">Sinai</placeName>. Back in Edessa, they interacted
          with <persName>Matthew the eunuch</persName>, a woman hiding in a monastery. They travelled to <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/104">Jerusalem</placeName>. Paul performed miracles and
          fled to <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/142">Nisibis</placeName>. John found him
          there, and Paul told him to return to Edessa. Paul died, and John died 8 months later. The
          story was set in the time of the Bishop <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/26">Rabbula</persName>.</note>
                    <note type="disambiguation">with John the priest and Rabbula</note>
                    <event type="attestation" xml:id="attestation1405-1" source="#bib1405-2">
                        <p xml:lang="en">Pawlōs is commemorated in <title ref="http://syriaca.org/work/1127">Paul the bishop and John the priest (text)</title>.</p>
                    </event>
